es/2014/5/27/1401188405744/Airbnb-008.jpg","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3phtf","standfirst":"The privatisation of care services works, but to have a truly open marketplace we must look to websites such as Airbnb and eBay","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2014-07-04T16:30:46Z","body":"<p>In the debate over whether public services should be privatised, a key point is often overlooked. A true market  requires an open marketplace in which people can browse and pick between service providers.</p><p>This was the thinking behind personal budgets in health and social care, which allow individuals to decide how to spend their allocated money for support, and there are clear benefits to this approach. Those receiving certain health and social care services need more control and choice over who they are buying services from. For some services this already exists, with customers having direct access to providers. In theory, providers should also have direct access to a market of consumers which is rapidly growing. But at the moment, there is no coherent marketplace.</p><p>We need the whole sector to be thrown open so that the benefits of personal budgets can be realised. It should not just be the same handful of companies providing certain services. There are a great number of service providers who can help with the welfare needs of families, but today it is hard for people to work out which ones are more suitable. Individuals paying for care are left at the mercy of Google to find a good provider, restricted to seeing companies with the biggest advertising budgets.</p><p>Local authorities do their best to coordinate providers, commission care and help connect families with those who can help. However, when people find suitable providers it's hard for them to tell if they are any good unless an organisation is regulated by the Care Quality Commission. Imagine, for example, if you lived 300 miles from an elderly relative and wanted to help them access the best services for their particular needs. Even if there is plenty of local information, that's not going to help you work out what the best option is when you are miles away.</p><p>It's like looking for holiday accommodation or secondhand books back when all we had to judge them by was adverts posted in the local newsagent or on a library noticeboard. Today, there are lots of simple ways you can find out what people think of services before you buy or try them for yourself. Services such as TripAdvisor, Airbnb and eBay have revolutionised how we shop online. Anyone, anywhere, can see who is offering what and – crucially – what other people think of it.</p><p>An Amazon-style marketplace is desperately needed for adult social care and children's services. The benefits from a system like this go beyond giving people choice; it would allow the people using these services to get truly personalised help tailored to their specific needs.</p><p>Councils could also use the service to plan for the future, identifying trends in what people are buying. Too often the state only knows what people really need or want when a crisis point has already been reached. Local and national portals giving information about health and social care providers would give valuable insight into new issues emerging on the horizon.</p><p>The public sector also needs a more efficient supply chain because of the cost pressure on home care providers for example. Small providers who don't struggle under the burden of large overheads should have the opportunity to deliver services directly to local users. The council focus could then shift to vetting and policing, in case problems arise.</p><p>With a open market, the role of the state could be as guardian and assurer of quality rather than the de facto service provider. If this change occurred then massive energy would be released into the actual provision of services from other sources.</p><p>This model of privatisation means that the state is still accountable for public safety and quality, whether that be child protection services or careers advice. Doubtless local authorities or NHS bodies will remain the preferred provider for many. But personal budgets could mean wholesale decommissioning of public sector contracts, freeing resources to focus on assessment, quality and better outcomes.</p><p><em>• Want your say? Email sarah.marsh@theguardian.com to suggest contributions to the network.</em></p><p><strong>Not already a member? </strong><a href=\"https://register.theguardian.com/local-government/\" title=\"\"><strong>Join us now</strong></a><strong> for more comment, analysis and the latest job opportunities in local government. </strong></p>","headline":"Do we need an Amazon-style website for social care services?","trailText":"<p><strong>Penny Osborne: </strong>The privatisation of care services works, but to have a truly open marketplace we must look to websites such as Airbnb and eBay</p>","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"theguardian.com","showInRelatedContent":"true","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/5/27/1401188405744/Airbnb-008.jpg","wordcount":"679","commentable":"true","internalContentCode":"437884775","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"9091205","isPremoderated":"false","byline":"Penny Osborne","internalPageCode":"2099292","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-06-04T08:38:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/local-government-network/2014/may/28/do-we-need-amazon-style-website-for-social-care","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/local-government-network/2014/may/28/do-we-need-amazon-style-website-for-social-care","tags":[{"id":"public-leaders-network/public-leaders-network","webTitle":"Public Leaders Network","type":"keyword","sectionId":"public-leaders-network","sectionName":"Public Leaders Network","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/public-leaders-network/public-leaders-network","apiUrl":"http://beta.co