eople think . Photograph: Ole Spata/  Ole Spata/dpa/Corbis","picdarUrn":"GD*37955853","width":"620"}}]}]},{"webTitle":"Signed, sealed, delivered","webPublicationDate":"2006-07-06T10:11:16Z","sectionName":"UK news","sectionId":"uk-news","id":"uk/2006/jul/06/post.publicservices","fields":{"standfirst":"The Post Office is one of the few public services left ... or is it? As Shrewsbury faces the closure of its central post office and the transferral of its services to the basement of the local branch of WH Smith, John Harris visits the town, and others like it, to find out what the communities think about the creeping privatisation","hasStoryPackage":"false","lastModified":"2006-07-06T10:11:16Z","body":"A couple of weeks ago, a letter-cum-leaflet was circulated around Shrewsbury, in which the Post Office announced new plans for its operations in the Shropshire town. By November, it said, it was aiming at shutting down Shrewsbury's central post office, shifting its staff elsewhere, and entering \"a franchise agreement with WH Smith, who will manage Shrewsbury's Post Office branch from their existing premises at the Darwin shopping centre\". As it turned out, Shrewsbury was not alone: there were identical plans for Swansea, Slough, Ashton-under-Lyne and Hammersmith in west London. Thus ensued a media bunfight: the Post Office talked about a \"partnership between two trusted organisations\", while the Communication Workers Union said the scheme was \"disgraceful and scandalous\", privatisation in all but name.<P>By way of assuring any sceptics that Smith's - which is set to house the new operation in the basement of its Darwin centre shop - was the right kind of company to take over the post office, the Shrewsbury letter paid tribute to the fact that that its sells \"a wide range of newspapers, magazines, stationery, books and home entertainment products\". If there were any creeping doubts about why dealing in paperbacks, rulers and pens should put anyone in the frame for handling parcels, letters and - oh, yes - large amounts of cash, the letter did not reflect them. Smith's, it claimed, had \"the customer focus, appropriate knowledge and retail experience to enable them to continue to provide a high standard of service to our customers\". Somewhere within those words, there perhaps lurked the belief that currently dictates whole swathes of our national life, once crisply summed up by Sir Richard Branson: \"If you can run one business, you can run any business.\"<P>For 53-year-old Barbara Davies, a nursing assistant who uses Shrewsbury's post office to pay her bills and do the lottery, none of this made much sense. \"I don't think they know what they're doing,\" she says. \"Why would WH Smith be any good at what the Post Office does? I actually thought the staff were being transferred, and they're not. It's just a waste.\" Sixty-six-year-old Peter Crompton, meanwhile, is only too keen to tell me about his wounded sense of civic pride: \"A town the size of Shrewsbury should have its own post office,\" he says. \"And anyway, I would imagine there'll be all sorts of teething troubles. Look at what the Post Office does - they're not things you can just get people in off the street to do, are they?\"<P>The fate of Britain's post offices is hardly the sexiest of political issues, easily maligned as the preserve of tweedy nostalgists, and a little too drab and functional to engage the passions of the kind of people who fret about corporate power. Yet it sits squarely on the fault line that defines so much modern debate - the questions of where we should draw the line between public and private, and when the untrammelled free market should be held at bay. For Conservatives - and particularly rural ones - it points up the tension between what remains of Thatcherism and their attachment to what might be termed the British Way of Life; for New Labourites, there is a similar disjunction between all their talk about the wonders of community and how that sits with the apparent belief that private is always better than public.<P>On the fringes of the news agenda, all this is bubbling away. In the House of Commons, early day motions (resolutions to which MPs can sign up, but that have no real parliamentary oomph) about the Post Office seem to appear on a weekly basis. Trawl the news archives, and you find a raft of stories about local post office revolts, not least when it comes to the actions of the UK's supermarkets: in 2004, for example, Tesco bought the T&S chain of convenience stores, turned them into Tesco Express outlets, and - to howls of complaint that included the voice of David Cameron, apparently cross that a shop in his Witney constituency was among the victims - promptly announced plans to close 40 of the post office counters that came with them. From time to time, such protests even come with the fragrant whiff of celebrity endorsement: in 2004, when the axe was taken to nearly half of London's post offices and plans were announced to close the post office on raffish Westbourne Grove in Notting Hill, signatories on a petition included Damon Albarn, Angela Rippon, Ruby Wax and Helen Fielding.<P>Under New Labour's watch, the Post Office has certainly had a very mixed time of it. Last year saw the closure of 1,352 post offices; in 2004, the figure was 1,278. Predictions of the demise of the letter and the parcel have proved way off the mark: the age of eBay and Amazon has meant that in the last six or seven years, revenue from mail has remained fairly steady. What has really hurt Britain's post offices is the fast decline in the kind of business that ties the citizen to the state: last year, revenue from \"government business\" - benefits, chiefly, plus things such as road tax and passports - dropped by &pound;168m.<P>Behind this lies not only our increased fondness for paying up via the internet and telephone, but the fact that some of the post office's most important roles seem to have been deliberately chiselled away. Benefit claimants and pensioners are now encouraged to open bank accounts, and the Post Office Card Account - the electronic replacement for the old benefit book, used by the remaining 4.3 million people who haven't been pushed into the arms of Barclays, Lloyds et al - is due to be wound up in 2010. As of the end of this month, the long-standing job of selling TV licences will go; that contract has gone to PayPoint, a private consortium recently hailed as \"one of the stock market's best performers\". By way of a counterbalance, 2003 saw the arrival of a &pound;150m-a-year subsidy to rural post offices (after the EU had kindly decided it did not represent \"unfair state aid\"), but that will expire in 2008. What happens after that is under review: as is the New Labour way, the official line from the Department of Trade Industry is that \"no decision has been made\".<P>Come the belated promotion of Gordon Brown, this would make for a very interesting political subplot. Which side of him will win out: the penny-pinching free-marketeer, keen to propel us into a privately run future cracked up to be somehow inevitable, or the moral communitarian who occasionally makes an appearance in his speeches? \"A town is more than a marketplace\" is one of his most oft-heard soundbites; that being the case, doesn't the red Post Office sign represent something more than mere business?<P>For his former ministerial colleague Kate Hoey, the MP for Vauxhall and chair of the all-party sub-post offices group, the auguries look pretty grim. She recently put down an early day motion protesting against the end of the Card Account, which has so far attracted the support of 366 MPs, though it does not sound as if the right people are listening. \"I personally think that there's a big move to say that the Post Office need no longer be in the public sector,\" she says. \"If you chip away at it over and over again, then what I think might happen is this: even though you have manifesto commitments that the Post Office will stay in the public sector, you've actually made it untenable.\"<P>The places soon to be subsumed into WH Smith are crown post offices, currently wholly owned by Royal Mail; in that context, it is difficult to avoid the conclusion that the plans represent simple privatisation. However, much of the ongoing disquiet surrounds the sub-post offices that make up 97% of the Post Office network, contracted out to small businesspeople and often run as part of local shops; the places that sit at the heart of the belief that the Post Office delivers a heartwarming public service.<P>Here, there is a huge ongoing revolt. On the face of it, the aforementioned Card Account does not earn post offices much money - they get 8p per &pound;100 cashed, though in ensuring that people come into post offices to get their benefits, it actually serves to generate revenue from selling other goods. When it goes, the Federation of Sub-Post Masters reckons, local post offices will lose 10% of their income, a prospect dreadful enough to have led more than a million people to sign a petition drawing attention to \"a vital service to communities in both urban and rural areas ... threatened by the government's withdrawal of services\". In Hoey's estimation, \"This is the big litmus test - if the government goes ahead with it, they might as well announce that they've no interest in keeping post offices throughout the country.\"<P>On the way to Shrewsbury, I stop at three sub-post offices. In Eardisley, a well-maintained hamlet in Herefordshire, 32-year-old Ewan Cardwell's business stands as a shining testament to the Post Office's belief that the people who run its services must now diversify or die: the post counter sits next to a shop that sells second-hand books, reading glasses, a small selection of DVDs and local maps. Next door, Cardwell's sister Briar runs a restaurant and bar at which her brother works the late shift; its licence now extends until 2am at weekends, after which he has to see to the pensions and parcels at nine the next morning. \"It's important we're here,\" he says. \"If the post office went, it'd be another nail in the village's coffin.\"<P>This morning, there is a succession of customers: passing lorry drivers, the odd pram-pushing mum, and a steady stream of local pensioners, at least half of whom do their business via the Pin machine reserved for the Card Account. \"If that goes,\" says Cardwell, \"it'll be a nightmare. Going all the way back to when they got rid of the pension book, I feel very strongly about the way we've been treated. Some of the letters sent out to pensioners [by the Department of Work and Pensions] have been really anti-Post Office, just pushing people away from us and towards the banks. The government seems to be against us, and I really don't know why.\"<P>Seven miles down the road in Kington, a market town whose peppering of vacant shops and peeling facades suggest an uneasy kind of future, there is a sizeable Victorian post office; the kind of place that employs a small handful of counter staff and has sidelines in Sellotape and Jiffy bags rather than cheap lager and ginger cake. The postmaster here is 51-year-old Paul Calverley, who recently chucked in his job as the head of development at ITV Wales, quit commuting to Cardiff and opted for a \"lifestyle change\". Yesterday, he tells me, &pound;10,904 passed over his counters in benefit payments. \"It's a lot, isn't it?\" he says. \"You can understand why the banks want a piece of it.\"<P>As things stand, he claims to make a reasonable living, bolstered by the money he gets from the Royal Mail for rental of the sorting office around the back, though when I ask him about the future, his expression rather darkens. \"The government is very good at talking about change, but it's very bad at managing it,\" he says. \"We know change is coming but we've got no clear steer on what the government wants the Post Office to be. At the moment, we're the one kind of interface that they have on the high street. But do they want that? I want to know where we'll be in five years' time.\"<P>The sentiments are echoed 30 miles up the road in Shropshire, where a post office serves Bent Lawnt, a settlement so small that it isn't on the map. Here, Christina Pickett has been the postmistress for 20 years, running the shop with her partner Jenny Jones, who sees to a grocery sideline whose most head-turning current special offer promises six cans of Carlsberg Export for &pound;3.50. On the post side, eBay has given them a lift and pensions and benefits are just about ticking over. They also set great store by the role that goes way beyond commerce: sorting people out with jobs and services, raising the alarm if a regular customer fails to show up. What bothers them is what might happen next. \"It sometimes feels like we're in limbo,\" says Jones. \"It'd be nice to refit the post office, but what are we going to be doing? I wish we knew.\"<P>Back in Shrewsbury, my day ends in a churchyard opposite the post office, sheltering from the sun in the company of an official from the Communication Workers Union named Jim Reeves, here to address the understandable fears of the 14 staff whose working lives are about to take a very unexpected turn. The WH Smith scheme, he says, is a new development - \"the first time that we've seen a major retailer get handed a significant number of post offices\". Those in charge claim there is \"no commitment to go any further\", although further deals are \"a possibility\"; the union suspects that what is currently under way actually amounts to a pilot scheme. As is so often the case when the public is turned private, the wages do not quite match up: from what he has heard, whereas a counter clerk employed by the post office will be on basic pay of &pound;18,000, WH Smith is offering between &pound;14,000 and &pound;15,000. (WH Smith responded to this with the claim that \"we don't discuss any remuneration packages for existing or new employees with anyone other than the individual involved\".)<P>Crown Post Offices lost &pound;50m last year, which, its management claims, makes outsourcing their sources increasingly appealing. In the words of a spokesman, \"Anything that enables us to provide the full range of services in town centres, we will look at. Partnerships are one way of doing that.\" Reeves gives that short shrift: \"It's Royal Mail that owns the Post Office, and last year they turned a profit of &pound;537m.\"<P>Just before I leave town, I pop back to the post office to talk to a few more customers. If it is easy to assume that everything we have been talking about is the preserve of trade unionists or pensioners or tweedy nostalgists, my last encounter provides a neat counterpoint. Seventeen-year-old Emily Bacon, a student with a part-time job at French Connection, has just been to the post office to sort herself out with traveller's cheques and holiday insurance before a week-long holiday in Magaluf. When I ask her what she thinks of the Post Office's plans, she looks perturbed, to say the least.<P>\"It's just stupid,\" she says. \"This place has been open for ages, and everyone in Shrewsbury uses it, so what are they doing? The people they're giving it to are here to sell books and papers, not handle large quantities of money. And it's unfair that people in there are going to lose their jobs.<P>\"It's good the way it is,\" she says. \"Why move it to the bottom of WH Smith?\"","headline":"Signed, sealed, delivered","trailText":"The Post Office is one of the few public services left ... or is it? As Shrewsbury faces the closure of its central post office and the transferral of its services to the basement of the local branch of WH Smith, <b>John Harris</b> visits the town, and others like it, to find out what the communities think about the creeping privatisation.","newspaperPageNumber":"10","shouldHideAdverts":"fal