rs - have worked together to find solutions most appropriate to their communities. Often this means rethinking pricing, including how subsidies can be used most effectively to benefit the poorest, and whether there is an appropriate role for private companies. Aid should be directed at these community-driven projects and not at promoting specific doctrines, whether espousing the virtues of liberalisation or public supply.    <br />  <strong>Robin Simpson   </strong><br />  Consumers International  </p><p>Maurice Terry of Watervoice (Letters, December 2) raises the important issue of water affordability. Much of the problem could be solved if water prices were reduced by curbing the excessive profits of the water companies. Since 1990, the very modest shareholdings which my wife and I hold in Anglian Water have produced more in dividends and capital repayments than we have paid the same company for our water supply.  </p><p>For such a basic utility, it cannot be right that shareholders have benefited to this extent at the expense of users and investment. Perhaps it is not only in developing countries that utility privatisation should be abandoned?    <br />  <strong>Bob Booth</strong><br />  Leighton Buzzard, Beds  </p>","headline":"Flow of profits to the water industry","trailText":"<p><strong>Letters: </strong> Privatisation of services such as water is an emotive issue (Comment, December 1).</p>","newspaperPageNumber":"29","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/x6hq","wordcount":"315","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"5077296","allowUgc":"false","isPremoderated":"false","internalPageCode":"24542","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2004/dec/03/water.guardianletters","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/environment/2004/dec/03/water.guardianletters","tags":[{"id":"environment/water","webTitle":"Water","type