onsibilities will pass in November to elected police and crime commissioners. Despite voting against commissioners, Prescott now aspires to be one of them. Private companies will not be able to arrest suspects, and they will not be solely responsible for investigating crimes. The public will always see police officers patrolling their neighbourhoods, responding to 999 calls and leading investigations. But the private sector can help to deliver behind-the-scenes services better and at lower cost. This frees up money for the frontline and enables us to make best use of policing's most valuable asset – the sworn officer. Under Blair, Labour understood the value of innovation in public services. How revealing that today they are the party against reform.<br /><a href=\"http://www.nickherbert.com/\" title=\"\"><strong>Nick Herbert MP</strong></a><br /><em>Minister of state for policing and criminal justice</em></p>","headline":"Prescott's U-turns","trailText":"<strong>Letters:</strong> John Prescott did not have his current grave concerns about privatisation in policing when, in 2002, his government allowed private companies to run police detention and escort services","newspaperPageNumber":"37","shouldHideAdverts":"false","publication":"The Guardian","showInRelatedContent":"true","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/363je","wordcount":"213","commentable":"false","internalContentCode":"387103273","allowUgc":"false","internalOctopusCode":"5911557","isPremoderated":"false","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-03-09T00:00:00Z","internalPageCode":"1715135","productionOffice":"UK","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2012-03-11T21:00:10Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/mar/08/prescott-privatisation-policing","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk/2012/mar/08/prescott-privatisation-policing","tags":[{"id":"uk/police","webTitle":"Police","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/police","apiUrl":"htt